metadata.name: The String #359
metadata.description:
|| Anniversary project for FX(hash) 1st birthday ||

Each virtual object consists of 365 lights.
Each light represents one day of the year.

We go through every single day, thinking it's all crucial. Yet, from a perspective, it all gets compressed into a single thread. Some of the events are brighter and more memorable. Others just blend or fade away.

I welcomed November 2021 with huge excitement and celebration. The joyful beginning of the month was followed by weeks of misery, anxiety, denial, and acceptance. It was a hard time, but in the long run, it was liberating and started a process of change. Change that happens dynamically to this day.

I couldn't join you last year, but I'm celebrating with you today!



In memory of my Dad.



Donations:
40% ‚Äì Savepakistan - Flood Relief Fundraiser
10% ‚Äì Three.js

metadata.name: just one long day #122
metadata.description: It's just a very long day. 365 revolutions around the sun, 8,760 hours and thousands of unfamiliar eyes waiting for the next morning. What does it mean to be stuck in one day? When everything around you is changing, living, breathing, dying, only you alone, like a stone statue. Nothing can touch you, and your feelings are externally muted to a minimum. Calm, joy, fear, anxiety, despair. You don't seem to have lost the ability to live, but you are somehow helpless and immobile. All your thoughts and experiences flow through your empty body, driving you insane. Everything around you distorts and changes in your eyes. And all you can do is remind yourself that it's just one long day. And I hope your tomorrow comes very soon.

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #598
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specterüëªpixel‚¨õlatte‚òï, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents‚Äîthe small moving circles‚Äîthat get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Cradle #384
metadata.description:
Billions of years old, ancient remains decay across our Solar System. Mere transient visitors to our star, their ephemeral presence on our worlds is embodied in their creations. In the shadow of their megalithic constructions, we wonder what they might have brought to us.

They brought life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'f' - render at full speed
'space' - stop/continue rendering

The image quality gradually improves over time. The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.

metadata.name: Ligare #127
metadata.description:
Ligare doesn‚Äôt begin in the same form as it ends, its past shapes the whole of its being. I often find myself wrestling with composition in generative work, a friend of mine put it best: ‚Äúit‚Äôs tough to think outside of a box you‚Äôve created.‚Äù

If we saw stars only for what they are, there would be no constellations.


The piece makes use of fxparams, which asks you to join the creative process, follow your intuition, and find the form that *feels* best to you :)


After creation, each Ligare can be exported as a plottable SVG <3
Press ‚Äò1‚Äô, ‚Äò2‚Äô, or ‚Äò3‚Äô to change the size of the PNG output
Press ‚Äòv‚Äô to render the image as an SVG
Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to return to the PNG render instance

This piece is optimized to be plotted at 11x14‚Äù with a 0.5mm pen.
You may change the page dimensions and margin size, as well as pen size so that you can use different media if you choose to plot this yourself:

To change the page dimensions and margin size, press ‚Äòw‚Äô and adjust the url parameters by the inch.
Margin is changed by the hundredth of an inch, ex: 0.5in would be ‚Äòmarg=50‚Äô.
To change pen size, press ‚Äòc‚Äô and adjust the url parameters accordingly. Pen size is also changed by the hundredth of a millimeter, for example penSize=35 is 0.35mm.

Changing the page dimensions may alter the details of your output slightly, as the piece is meant to be displayed primarily with its default url parameters.

Created by Chris McCully using p5.js, p5.svg.js, and chroma.js
(2023)
